      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "No worries at all! I apologize for the sudden goblin monologue; I just get a bit too excited when discussing accounting because I imagine the numbers are just waiting for a goblin to come along and steal them all.\n\nTo clear up the confusion: **Salvage Value** is the estimated amount of money you expect to get when you finally sell or scrap the asset at the end of its life. It's the \"residual value\" that remains in the goblin's pocket after they've spent all their time hoarding the treasure. In your example, that $5,000 is what you'd get for the machinery after 5 years.\n\n**Useful Life**, on the other hand, is simply the estimated number of years the asset will be used before it becomes too broken or obsolete to be useful. It's the timeline the goblin plans to spend before they decide to move on and find a new dungeon to loot. In your example, the machinery is expected to serve you for 5 years.\n\nYou calculate depreciation by taking the difference between the total cost and the salvage value, then spreading that difference evenly over the useful life. So, you subtract the $5,000 salvage value from",
